WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.840
 - Hello and welcome to this lecture

00:00:01.840 --> 00:00:03.720
 on the structure of a django application.

00:00:03.720 --> 00:00:06.620
 It's a little early to be going through all the detail

00:00:06.620 --> 00:00:07.920
 and there'll be some things that we're not really

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:10.680
 going to understand until a little bit later in the course.

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:13.520
 But I wanted to sort of show you the lay of the land

00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:15.720
 so that as we add features you realize

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:19.360
 that there's sort of a method to the madness.

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:23.320
 And so django is a way of building web applications.

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:26.400
 Django has a pattern within itself

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:29.760
 that organizes folders in a certain way

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:31.760
 and puts files in certain places.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:36.040
 And we're gonna build these projects and applications

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:39.040
 and you're like, why are these things

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:40.560
 organized the way they are?

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:42.480
 Well, it has to do with the fact that if you go

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:45.220
 from one django project to another django project,

00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:47.460
 you can, you know, fit right in

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:49.140
 and understand how things are going to work.

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:52.440
 So the important terminology that's, I don't know,

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:55.360
 a bit frustrating is there is projects and applications.

00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:59.180
 And from django has this notion of,

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:02.320
 you have applications and you might have a project

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:04.120
 which is really basically a website.

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:06.440
 And then, you know, some applications.

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:07.700
 But if you had two projects,

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:09.780
 you could share applications between them.

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:13.760
 And so it's one or more applications per project

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:15.920
 with the ability to potentially reuse

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:19.080
 a application across multiple projects.

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:22.360
 And so we're gonna work with my dj4esamples,

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:24.160
 which I hope you have downloaded somewhere,

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:26.200
 at least so that you can look at the files,

00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:28.240
 look at the folders, look at the names of the files,

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:29.920
 look at the contents of the files.

00:01:29.920 --> 00:01:31.400
 This will all make more sense

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:34.240
 when you get a little farther down the road.

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:39.200
 So here is an ls statement, ls -l dj4esamples and hello.

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:42.280
 This is within the folder dj4esamples.

00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:44.120
 There are two basic folders.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:47.280
 One is, in effect, the project-wide settings,

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:51.240
 which is the same name as the folder that we're in.

00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:55.400
 So it's dj4esamples/dj4esamples.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:57.140
 And then there is the first application,

00:01:57.140 --> 00:01:59.040
 which is hello.

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:00.460
 And there's a couple things here,

00:02:00.460 --> 00:02:04.420
 like the __init.py, you'll notice it's an empty file.

00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:07.920
 It's just some bookkeeping that helps Python know

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:11.000
 that there are files that contain classes

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:12.100
 and objects in here.

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:17.800
 Settings.py and urls.py and wgsi.py

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:20.720
 is kind of like the traffic cop

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:23.440
 for this entire application that routes things

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:26.280
 coming into the right, this entire project

00:02:26.280 --> 00:02:28.360
 that routes things to the right application.

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:31.400
 And then within the application, we have some files.

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:33.560
 And you're really gonna learn a lot

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:34.840
 about object-oriented programming

00:02:34.840 --> 00:02:37.800
 because all these files contain objects.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.840
 So Django is a large piece of software

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:43.480
 and you change its behavior by defining objects

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:45.200
 that accomplish things and then, in effect,

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:46.840
 registering those objects.

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:50.040
 So a common thing will be to take something like, you know,

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:53.200
 admin.py or models.py, create a data model

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:55.680
 and then tell the admin user interface

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:59.440
 that you didn't write how to show your model

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:01.960
 and so you write stuff in admin.py

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:05.920
 to communicate into the admin user interface

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:09.320
 how your data model that Django currently knows nothing about

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:11.680
 is supposed to be shown, et cetera, et cetera.

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:13.260
 And so there's a lot of files

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:16.400
 and we will talk through these files.

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:20.560
 Now, this is an example of a request response.

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:24.340
 It's a web application and so what we'll talk about

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:26.920
 is once a request makes it into the server,

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:29.000
 it's gonna do some work and then produce a response.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.480
 But in that, we're gonna look at all of the work

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:33.760
 that goes back and forth.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.600
 And there's effectively like a routing step

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:38.560
 where it picks what part of your application

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:40.840
 to run this route this request to.

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:44.920
 There is a view part which is going to receive it

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:47.400
 and potentially store data.

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:49.680
 Some would call that the model.

00:03:49.680 --> 00:03:51.460
 The storing of the data is certainly the model,

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:54.300
 but the receiving of the possibly new input data

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:55.800
 like you're gonna create a new thing,

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:57.260
 that would be the model.

00:03:57.260 --> 00:04:00.160
 And then the view, at some point you gotta finish it

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:01.780
 and send something back out

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:03.640
 and that's the purpose of the view.

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:07.120
 We call this pattern for building web applications,

00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:08.600
 model view controller.

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:10.800
 And it's not like you can't build applications

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.600
 any other way, it's just by saying,

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:16.240
 it's a terminology that I can say going forward,

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:18.260
 that's the model, that's the view,

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:19.860
 and that's a controller function.

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:22.060
 And you don't have to know it right now,

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:25.200
 but these are words that they're loaded

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:27.940
 and have valuable meaning to us to be able to do.

00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.320
 So at some point in this picture on the left side,

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:32.820
 we have a browser.

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:35.580
 DOM stands for the document object model.

00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:38.520
 And at some point the person clicks somewhere

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:41.020
 in the current web page they're looking at

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:43.980
 and the web browser intercepts that

00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:47.060
 and says, oh okay, I've got your click right here.

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:49.060
 The web browser intercepts it

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:51.580
 and then makes a socket connection across the internet,

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:54.580
 which we've seen before, and then does a get request.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:57.540
 And that is what then goes into the server.

00:04:57.540 --> 00:05:00.340
 And so the three functions are the routing,

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.060
 the views, and the models.

00:05:02.060 --> 00:05:05.540
 And there is an overall configuration file,

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:09.300
 the settings.py, which is sort of how you just say,

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:11.780
 oh, here's my view files, read these view files,

00:05:11.780 --> 00:05:12.980
 read these model files.

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:16.220
 So the settings.py kinda controls everything.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.140
 But when a request first comes in,

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:20.460
 it consults urls.py.

00:05:20.460 --> 00:05:22.860
 And then for the project,

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:25.660
 and then it will include urls.py's

00:05:25.660 --> 00:05:27.500
 from each of the applications.

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:30.820
 So once it's chosen what view to run,

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:33.780
 it looks at the URL, pulls out the pieces of the URL,

00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:37.080
 and finds the views in views.py.

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:41.180
 That's a Python file that has the destinations

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:43.340
 for these incoming URLs.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:46.000
 There's a file called forms.py, which we'll see later,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.820
 that is used to make the forms aspect,

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:52.980
 the part that you fill in as pretty as possible.

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:55.700
 And then we take the resulting data

00:05:55.700 --> 00:05:58.020
 that we're gonna send back, and we merge that in

00:05:58.020 --> 00:05:59.740
 through what's called a template.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:02.420
 And then if there's any data that we need stored,

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:05.980
 we use, we call the model and we store that in a database.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:08.680
 And there's this file called model.py,

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:12.300
 which informs how we store data in the database.

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:14.200
 And then when that's all done,

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:17.560
 we read potentially new data from the database,

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:20.920
 merge that into a template, and then send a response back

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:24.700
 to the browser, and then that response is all shown

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:25.540
 to the end user.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:29.880
 And so that really is the request into the server

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:31.380
 through a Django application,

00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:33.140
 pulling data from various places,

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:35.060
 merging a template back in,

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:40.060
 and then sending a response back to the application.

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:44.580
 So up next, we're gonna talk about virtual hosting.

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:46.660
 Now, in general, you're not gonna have to worry about this.

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:50.180
 It just kind of explains how something like Python Anywhere

00:06:50.180 --> 00:06:52.940
 is able to manage a whole lot of domains

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:54.560
 on a single system.

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.140
 (upbeat music)

